product_title: The Honest Company Honest Sunscreen Lotion SPF 30 2-pack 3.0oz
review_body: I'm giving this product a 1 star  because I can't think of any positives related to it.  I purchased this two pack of sunscreen from a local warehouse because I thought it was a good deal and because I thought it was a healthier alternative to traditional chemical laden sunscreens. I'm not sure if the latter is true, but the former is not, since it was absolutely not effective in any way and was just a waste of money.  First, this product goes on very heavy--consistency and smell is similar to melted wax.  It does not rub into the skin very well and is not at all moisturizing.  In fact, I would say that it actually dries your skin out.  As far as wear throughout the day, this product seemed to cause me to sweat a lot more than usual.  I am generally not a noticeable sweater, but this product brought forth the sweat beads like no other. Not only that, it was was hard to miss the fact that I was sweating because the sweat condensed on the skin in the form of white ooze, so i looked like a melting wax sculpture.  As for sun protection, that is non-existent.  I had a noticeable color line from my where my clothing ended and where my skin began even though I applied a heavy coating of this sunscreen (since it's really the only option you have since it doesn't apply well).  I'm putting this out on the curb for some other sucker to have.

product_title: Scream Tattoo Ink 30-pack Set 1-oz Bottles -Tattoo Supplies-
review_body: As a professional tattoo artist, I remember receiving these in a kit that I bought, when I first began years and years ago. The problem with these inks are: They are cheap. You get what you pay for. At the time, those colors are bright, easy to apply and easy to wipe off. Years of experience later, it is not a good ink that is easily wiped off. It is not a good ink that settles if not used in a few days. The pigments are too large, that is why it settle so fast. Also, after having the ink in my arms for what is now 6 years, every tattoo that was done in it has faded dramatically. The yellow was the first to go, reds turned marbled and the blacks are now blue-ish. That being said, excellent to practice with, not excellent if you now own the business you started at. Spend the money, use Intenze or Kuro Sumi. Just remember, it is extremely difficult to mix Intenze for new colors. Kuro Sumi is bit easier. I recommend that no one buys these inks. Also, I have seen too many reactions to the red, yellow and greens.

review_headline: Decent middle quality blades readily available in many shops.

I would consider these to be solid middle level razors with decent shaving action (but nothing superb). If you have thick hair, this may not be good enough. If you prefer to pay more for better quality, then something like Feather and KAI, both from Japan are great, and if you prefer to pay less and still go higher up in quality you can try something like Astra, which is from Russia. product_title: Philips Norelco Nose trimmer Series 3300, nose and eyebrows, 2 eyebrow combs, NT3355/49
review_headline: Fast and effective. Comparison to the Panasonic.
review_body:
I use this exclusively for nose trimming so I will only comment on that.
-It's a bit intimidating with the exposed blade but there is no pain or discomfort at all.
-With only a couple swirls around the nostril, the trimming is done. It only takes seconds.

Comparison to [[ASIN:B0049LUI9O Panasonic ER-GN30-K Nose, Ear n Facial Hair Trimmer Wet/Dry with Vortex Cleaning System]] which I have used for weeks.
-Panasonic takes much longer to get all the hairs because the blade is hidden behind a guard with only a few perforations for hair to get through. The Norelco has more exposed blade area which requires fewer passes. To put this in a time perspective, the Panasonic would take about 60 seconds to trim nose hair; the Norelco, 10 seconds.
-Both trim comfortably with minimal to no pain.
-The Panasonic has a wider, blunter tip so which is good if you are prone to shoving things too far up your nose.
-Overall, the Norelco is superior because it is so much faster and more efficient.

review_headline: UPDATE - Have to downgrade this review! Brush Now Broken & Unuseable!
review_body: Absolutely best brush I've ever used!  Love it. Was trying to find the right brush for a long time, this one is it. I've recently begun using Argan oil, and really appreciate the downloadable product info in conjunction with using Argan oil. Will not hesitate to promote and recommend. I must change this review to reflect the fact that an entire row of bristles broke and fe out of this brush. Regular brushing as usual and the row snapped out, the brush is now rendered useless because it does not cover the area of hair being brushed, properly. Now I have to begin a hunt for a replacement. Is it too much to ask for a product that will last longer than a few months. I have my grandmother's Fuller Brush from the 60's, it's still in mint condition!  I bought this new brush to give my vintage Fuller a rest, but sadly the brush is broken. I'm going to Fuller site now to see what they offer now, clearly their brush from over 50 years ago is far superior to this one. Will search for a brush at Fuller or somewhere else. UPDATE 1/13/15 - Rows & bristles fell out!  I'm now on the hunt for a brush again. It's disappointing, just when I thought I'd found a good one, this brush fell apart.  It was good while it lasted, it should have given more use than the time I used it and the amount of time it took for the rows to snap off and fall apart buy at your own risk!

product_title: Violight Slim Sonic Toothbrush
review_headline: Great sonic toothbrush for home or travel
review_body:
Ever since I bought my first sonic travel toothbrush, to use for travel, I decided I preferred it to any regular or battery powered toothbrush for daily use. The brand I used wasn't as good as this one, and stopped working after months of use. I was on my 3rd. I decided to try other brands, and like this one very much, for it's style and compactness, and the fact the power button is covered by the cap. While I normally prefer a larger brush head, this works so much better than the prior brand that the size difference is negligible. The cap has small air holes to allow the brush to dry while capped, and it can stand upright on a counter. It is about as thick as a large marker.

I don't know how long it will last, but I bought extra brush heads. This is the first of several brands I decided to try, but it gets 5 stars so far. It is more powerful than the prior, bulkier one I had. This one can easily fit in a purse and the cap is secure. It comes in many different colors/patterns.

product_title: Purederm Exfoliating Foot Mask - Peels Away Calluses and Dead Skin in 2 Weeks!
review_headline: Took 2+ weeks to arrive from South Korea via USPS
review_body:
Took 2+ weeks to arrive from South Korea which was frankly disappointing, however I am pleased with the results from the product.

I really don't know why reviewers tell you to soak your feet before using - it doesn't tell you to do that on the package at all. My wide, size 10 (woman's) foot just, just fit in the booties. I didn't understand from other reviews that there was an additional layer inside the booties (felt like the material dryer sheets are made from) that should mold/shape around your tootsies and up the sides of your feet, then the plastic booties keep all the goo in. Not suitable for walking around either, so RELAX. My feet felt cold the whole time and itchy/stinging but those of us who go thru hair-highlighting and facial scrubs know the drill. The wait was worth it. My feet haven't felt this good in a very long time. Glad I got the 3-pack for the summer.

So product 4 stars, delivery 3 stars I suppose.

product_title: Philips Sonicare HealthyWhite Electric Rechargeable Toothbrush Special Pack,  Hx6731/34
review_body:
A few years ago, my mom's friend and (very expensive) dentist recommended that we use Sonicare brushes instead of regular ones. That day, she went out and bought 4 of them. A year later, only my wife is using it. That should be the end of the product review but I'll go into a bit more detail:

The Bad:

1 - This brush will break after 1 year. Don't expect to get much more life out of it (either the battery will die or the tip that vibrates will break inside. non-repairable).

2 - You can not share the base of the brush with your partner by just switching the heads. While it will work, it will break the brush within 2 months.

3 - Expensive compared to a $5 traditional brush. The replacement heads are also expensive.

4 - Doesn't improve oral hygiene enough to be worth the cost.

The Good:

1 - It has a two minute timer. Since most of us are horrible at estimating time, the timer allows us to know when to stop brushing. Brushing a full two minutes leads to better oral hygiene compared to brushing 30 seconds to 1 minute; so the brush does "work". The cheaper alternative is to stick with a traditional brush and buy a 2 minute sand timer (or just use your smartphone).

2 - The grip feels good, the brush is different from a traditional brush and the vibrating makes you pay attention to what you are doing while brushing your teeth.

3 - When comparing to other rotary/vibrating brushes, you get what you pay for. It is a good quality brush.

Summary: Skip it; just brush longer with your regular tooth brush. Add some dental floss and mouth wash to the mix and you won't need this.

product_title: Nature's Gate Anise Natural Toothpaste 6 oz toothpaste
review_headline: Tasty toothpaste, not chalky or dehydrating, and also compatible with homeopathic remedies (5/5 green stars also)
review_body:
I have been alternating between Natureâs Gate Anise and Tomâs of Maine Antiplaque and Whitening toothpastes for a while and, although I like both, I think Natureâs Gate is overall better in terms of taste (Tomâs leaves an aftertaste and tends to dry out my mouth if I donât rinse really thoroughly). Another bonus of Natureâs Gate Anise flavor, besides the pleasant taste, is that itâs compatible with homeopathic remedies (mint reduces their effectiveness).

Natureâs Gate replaced the traditional sodium lauryl sulfate (SLS) with Sodium Lauroyl Sarcosinate to address the concerns over safety of SLS. When it comes down to it, regular toothpaste is basically a combination of an abrasive agent (such as calcium carbonate), a surfactant (such as SLS), and fluoride. If you donât want fluoride and you are worried about safety of the surfactants then a common home-made remedy is baking soda combined with sea salt (this acts as an abrasive and the baking soda also creates a more alkaline pH, neutralizing the acids that cause bacterial growth and tooth decay). Researching this option has just convinced me to try it for a while â the evidence looks convincing.

Overall Iâll give Natureâs Gate Crème de Anise toothpaste 5/5 gold stars for quality of the product and 5/5 âgreenâ stars based on the social and environmental aspects of producing it. More on social and environmental responsibility below:

Environmental and social impact: Natureâs Gate use post-consumer cardboard (and plastic) for packaging and soy-based inks for printing. Their products are also cruelty free and contain no animal-derived ingredients. Their certified organic ingredients are grown at a nearby farm (reducing fuel use) that uses rainwater and runoff from the Sierra Nevada snowpack for water supply. They also support WaterAid, which promotes rainwater solutions to provide clean drinking water in developing countries.

Terracycle offer recycling of toothpaste tubes (along with many other items such as deodorant, floss, mouthwash and toothbrushes) for people willing to collect several of them and ship them off. This recycling program is sponsored by Tomâs of Maine but actually you can recycle empty containers from any company. Itâs worth checking out Terracycle for recycling packaging in general - they provide free shipping labels. The alternative, if you are concerned about toothpaste tubes going to landfill, is to make your own baking soda and sea salt toothpaste at home!

On the fluoride front, the addition to fluoride to water (practiced in the US but not in most European countries) helps to reduce dental decay but also carries some risks. I think we (involuntarily) get enough fluoride in our water â supplementing this with the even more fluoride in toothpaste is unnecessary in my view, considering that there are several concerns regarding its use. Quick summary of fluoride dosage and toxicity: around 5 grams is a potentially lethal dose for an adult and 60 mg for an average 2 year old. If a child were to accidentally swallow less than half a tube of toothpaste (such as Colgate Kids), it could be fatal. Then, around 0.2 mg/kg body weight can cause gastrointestinal discomfort (i.e. 2.4 mg for a 12 kg 2 year old, or 12 mg for a 60 kg adult). A large strip of toothpaste contains around 2.25 mg of fluoride (and a truly pea-sized amount contains 0.3 mg) while a liter of municipal tap water usually contains 1 mg. So, the amount of fluoride in toothpaste is fairly significant if you use a lot of paste, brush your teeth often, and/or tend to swallow some of it. In addition to gastrointestinal discomfort, chronic exposure to fluoride in large amounts interferes with bone formation. Iâd rather eliminate the fluoride source in my toothpaste even if I choose to live with the fluoride in my tap water.ling of toothpaste tubes (along with many other items such as deodorant, floss, mouthwash and toothbrushes) for people willing to collect several of them and ship them off.
